ngland":"Brewood, Staffordshire, England","The Battle of Halidon Hill, Berwick-On-Tweed, Northumberland, England":"Berwick-upon-Tweed, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fowke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from the Middle English, Anglo-Norman French personal name  <i>Folk</i>,  <i>Fulk</i>,  <i>Fuke</i>.  Compare  Foxon  . For a variant form of the personal name  see  Foulkes  .  See also  Fudge  , which may sometimes be a variant form."],"variants":[{"name":"Fudge","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English, Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fulch</i> or <i>Fuche</i>, usually a pet form of Old French <i>Fulcher</i>, <i>Fucher</i> (see   Fulcher  ). Voicing of ‘ch’ to soft ‘g’ gave rise to <i>Fudge</i>. The name may sometimes have been interchangeable with <b>Fowke</b> (for which see   Foulk   1), derived from a pet form of this and other Old French personal names in <i>Fulc-</i>.","English: habitational name from Fuge, in Blackawton, Devon. This placename is composed of Old English <i>feoh</i> ‘cattle’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘farm, dairy farm, village’."]},{"name":"Folke","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke  ."]},{"name":"Fook","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke  ."]},{"name":"Foulk","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English and Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fulk</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, ultimately from an element meaning ‘folk, people’."]},{"name":"Fogg","meanings":["English (northern): possibly a variant of <b>Fowke</b> (see   Foulk   1). It may derive from Middle English <i>fogge</i> ‘aftermath’ (i.e. grass left to grow after the hay has been cut, also applied to long grass in a water meadow), especially in northern England, where the term occurs as a specifying element in minor placenames, but as it is not found on its own as a simplex name, the derivation is doubtful without some supporting evidence. The word <i>fogge</i>, which is probably of Old Norse origin, is still in use as a dialect term in Craven, Yorkshire, and in eastern Lancashire. modern English <i>fog</i> ‘thick mist’ is first attested in the 16th century and is unlikely to be the source of the surname."]},{"name":"Fuke","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke   and  compare  Fook  ."]},{"name":"Folk","meanings":["German: variant of   Volk   1 and, in North America, also an altered form of this. This form of the surname is also found in Czechia.","English: variant of   Foulk   1."]},{"name":"Focke","meanings":["North German, East Frisian, and Dutch: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Folco</i>, a pet form of various names beginning with <i>Folc-</i> or <i>Volk-</i>; cognate with   Foulk   1.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Foulk   1. See also   Foulks  ."]},{"name":"Foulke","meanings":["English (Derbyshire and Shropshire): variant of   Foulk  ."]},{"name":"Fulk","meanings":["English: variant of   Foulk   1.","Altered form of German   Volk   or   Falk  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":0,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":13,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":22,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Henry Fowke was born in 1315, in Brewood, Staffordshire, England, his father, Sir Richard Fowke, was 30 and his mother, Arabella Isabella de Beauchamp, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Mirabell Harrison. He died in 1369, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1315–1369":"1315–1369","–Female":"Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1285–1333":"1285–1333","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","1369":"1369","19 July 1333":"19. juuli 1333","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","1340":"1340","1285":"1285","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, England","The Battle of Halidon Hill, Berwick-On-Tweed, Northumberland, England":"Berwick-upon-Tweed, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1315–1369":"1315–1369","–Female":"Kuollut","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1285–1333":"1285–1333","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","1369":"1369","19 July 1333":"19. heinäkuuta 1333","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","1340":"1340","1285":"1285","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Brewoo